{"type":"message","id":"02f0dbc7","parentId":"482fd09c","timestamp":"2026-03-08T14:28:28.336Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Caddy is running as a reverse proxy to port 18789, which is the OpenClaw gateway. I don't want to interfere with that. I can either:\n\n1. Add a path-based route in Caddy for `/dashboard` that serves the HTML file\n2. Serve the dashboard on a separate port with a simple HTTP server\n\nLet me add a route to the Caddyfile so `/dashboard` serves the HTML file directly. This way it's accessible at `https://64.227.110.70/dashboard`.\n\nActually, the cleanest approach would be to add a `handle /dashboard*` block in the Caddyfile that serves the HTML file, or serve it from the file_server.\n\n\nI'll update the Caddyfile to configure a static file server for the dashboard path.","thinkingSignature":""},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tooluse_W7yinFI6okjE4x1yxtn6Bi","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# Create a web-accessible folder and copy the dashboard\nsudo mkdir -p /var/www/dashboard\nsudo cp ~/.openclaw/workspace/datafloat/mission-control.html /var/www/dashboard/index.html\nsudo chown -R caddy:caddy /var/www/dashboard\n\n# Update Caddyfile to serve /dashboard from that folder\nsudo tee /etc/caddy/Caddyfile > /dev/null << 'EOF'\n64.227.110.70 {\n    tls {\n        issuer acme {\n            dir https://acme-v02.api.letsencrypt.org/directory\n            profile shortlived\n        }\n    }\n\n    handle /dashboard* {\n        root * /var/www/dashboard\n        file_server\n    }\n\n    handle {\n        reverse_proxy localhost:18789\n    }\n\n    header X-DO-MARKETPLACE \"openclaw\"\n}\nEOF\n\nsudo caddy reload --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile 2>&1"}}],"api":"bedrock-converse-stream","provider":"amazon-bedrock","model":"us.anthropic.claude-sonnet-4-6","usage":{"input":1,"output":486,"cacheRead":88225,"cacheWrite":263,"totalTokens":88975,"cost":{"input":0.000003,"output":0.0072900000000000005,"cacheRead":0.0264674